# picking a programming language — a use-case-driven framework
#
# pulls together the c/rust/zig/go discussion and adds the categories those
# notes don't cover (web/app, mobile, data/ml, scripting). see also:
# [[why-learn-c]] [[c-to-rust-rewrite]] [[zig-notes]] [[go-notes]]
# [[gui-frameworks]]


# the meta-rule

# pick the language with the ecosystem that already solved your problem.
# not the prettiest syntax. not the fastest benchmark. the ecosystem.
#
# a language is mostly its libraries, its package manager, its build tools,
# its deployment story, and the size of its hiring pool. the syntax is the
# part you stop noticing after a week. the ecosystem is what you live with
# for years.


# the questions to actually ask

# 1. what does the problem look like?
#    - latency-sensitive system call → c / rust / zig
#    - networked service → go / rust / typescript / python
#    - one-off script → bash / python
#    - data analysis → python / r
#    - ml training → python
#    - mobile app → swift / kotlin / react native / flutter
#    - desktop gui → see [[gui-frameworks]]
#
# 2. what does deployment look like?
#    - single static binary, scp it anywhere → go / rust / zig
#    - container with runtime → python / node / ruby / java
#    - bundled into an os install → c (or system language of that os)
#    - distributed via app store → swift / kotlin
#
# 3. what's the existing team / codebase?
#    - if it's already python, write more python unless there's a real reason
#      to switch. polyglot codebases are expensive to maintain.
#    - the "what does the team already know" question usually beats every
#      technical consideration.
#
# 4. what's the hiring market?
#    - python, javascript, java, go — easy to hire for
#    - rust, kotlin, swift — moderate
#    - zig, ocaml, elixir, haskell — niche; you're hiring on cultural fit
#      more than skill availability
#
# 5. what's the library you need?
#    - "the language that has the library" wins almost every fight.
#    - need pytorch? python.
#    - need k8s api bindings? go.
#    - need a windows com interop? c# or rust with windows crate.
#    - need llvm bindings? c++ (or rust via inkwell).


# by use case (2026)

# systems / kernels / drivers / embedded
# - c — the substrate. still the default for kernels, libc, firmware.
# - rust — winning new security-critical work (drivers, browsers, crypto).
# - zig — c-style ergonomics with a modern build system; pre-1.0.
# - see [[c-to-rust-rewrite]] [[zig-notes]] for the long form.

# backend services / apis
# - go — default. boring, productive, fast enough, single binary, cloud-native.
# - rust — when go's gc pauses or perf ceiling actually matter (rare).
# - typescript (node / bun / deno) — if the team is already js, just stay.
# - python (fastapi) — if it's an ml-adjacent service or team is python-first.
# - java / kotlin — at enterprise scale with existing jvm infra.
# - elixir — if you want erlang-style fault tolerance and don't mind hiring.

# cli tools
# - go — fast to ship, single binary, cross-compiles trivially.
# - rust — for polish, perf, or when correctness matters (ripgrep, fd, bat).
# - zig — if it's tiny / embedded-adjacent.
# - python — only if you ship it with uv or pyinstaller; otherwise install
#   hell. fine for personal scripts.
# - bash — for <50 lines of glue. past that, rewrite in python or go.

# web frontend
# - typescript — the only real answer. plain javascript is for codebases that
#   predate 2018.
# - frameworks: react still dominates; svelte / solid / qwik are the
#   challengers; htmx if you want server-rendered with less js.
# - wasm via rust / go / zig is real for compute-heavy bits but not for
#   replacing the ui layer.

# mobile
# - ios native — swift + swiftui. uikit if you need older device support.
# - android native — kotlin + jetpack compose. java only for legacy.
# - cross-platform — react native (most mature), flutter (best ui control),
#   kotlin multiplatform (if you want native ui per platform with shared logic).
# - never native: do not pick c++ / qt for new mobile work in 2026.

# desktop gui
# - see [[gui-frameworks]] for the per-os picks.
# - cross-platform: tauri (rust + web ui), electron (still dominant, still
#   bloated), flutter desktop, .net maui.

# data science / analytics
# - python — pandas, polars, numpy, scikit-learn, matplotlib, jupyter.
#   no real competition.
# - r — if you're in stats / academia and that's the team norm.
# - sql — not a "programming language" but the single highest-roi thing on
#   this list. learn it well regardless of what else you pick.
# - julia — fast, elegant, niche; pick only if you have a specific reason.

# machine learning / ai
# - python — the only answer for training. pytorch, jax, transformers,
#   diffusers. everyone uses it including google.
# - for ai-application-layer code (calling apis, building agents): see
#   [[ai-integration-skill]] [[ai-eval-skill]]. python and typescript are
#   the two real choices; pick whichever your product is in.

# scripting / automation / glue
# - python — default. batteries-included, runs everywhere, easy enough.
# - bash — short, throwaway, system-level glue.
# - go — if you want the script to become a real tool people install.
# - powershell — windows-native; surprisingly good if you live in that world.
# - never pick perl for new code.

# game dev
# - c++ — unreal, custom engines. still the industry standard.
# - c# — unity. by far the easiest entry path.
# - gdscript — godot. great for indie / hobbyist; growing fast.
# - rust — bevy is real but pre-production-ready.
# - zig — game dev is a vocal niche of the zig community.


# the "learn one new language" question

# if you're picking a language to *learn* (not to ship in tomorrow), the
# value is in the model it teaches you, not the syntax:
#
# - c — how computers actually work. memory, layout, ub. see [[why-learn-c]].
# - rust — ownership, lifetimes, "make illegal states unrepresentable."
# - go — concurrency as a first-class language feature.
# - haskell / ocaml — pure functions, type-driven design, hindley-milner.
#   you'll bring these patterns back to whatever you actually use.
# - lisp / scheme / clojure — code as data, macros, repl-driven development.
# - sql — set-based thinking. underrated as a mental model.
# - prolog — logic programming. fully bends your brain; rare worth.
#
# rough order of mainstream payoff: c → rust → go → typescript → python →
# kotlin. anything beyond that is for taste.


# anti-patterns

# - picking a language because hn likes it this month
# - picking based on "fastest in this benchmark" — you almost certainly don't
#   need that perf
# - rewriting a working codebase to switch languages — almost never pays for
#   itself. add a new service in the new language at a boundary instead.
# - introducing a second language into a small team / small codebase to "use
#   the right tool for the job" — the cognitive overhead and tooling tax
#   usually eats the benefit.
# - learning a language by reading books for a year without writing anything.
#   write a small real thing in the first weekend.


# the one-liner

# the right language is the one with the library you need, that your team
# can hire for, that deploys the way your infra wants, in that order. syntax
# is the last thing on the list.
